posts.name: Jaxon
posts.cooked:
Hello. I need to get G-Code software to run our Techno-Isel LC series CNC router. I want to get Cut2D desktop, but I don’t know for sure if it will work with the post-processor. Since it is only listed as working with Aspire and VcarvePro here . Has anyone tried this or is familiar with technoCNC products and know what I should do here? I want an affordable way to generate GCode for this thing.

Thanks for the help in advance.

posts.name: sanddrag
posts.cooked: I used to post from InventorHSM or Fusion with the Fancuc - Generic Fanuc post and just manually delete the G28 G91 lines at the top and bottom, and the G43 H_ line. Worked great. Aside from that, it worked well. Nothing very non-standard about the Techno codes. G1, G2, G3, and maybe G81. That’s about all you need. Oh, and no helical arcs.

posts.name: Devin Castellucci
posts.cooked:
Cut2D Pro has a auto nesting feature which is super useful for saving money on material when doing large runs. It has the following Post-Processors listed for Techno Techno-Isel ATC (inch) ( .ncd) Techno-Isel ATC (mm) ( .ncd) Techno-Isel Arc (inch) ( .ncd) Techno-Isel Arc ATC (inch) ( .ncd)

You can also get HSM for SolidWorks for free as an educator. I’m ~90% sure that BOTH programs use the same list of post processors, the Pro version just has WAY more tools for working on manipulating your vectors and toolpaths.

posts.name: Brian Wagg
posts.cooked:
Fanuc is a style of CNC controller. More accurately it’s a brand of CNC controller. Very common in industry and has its own “flavour” of G-code.

For example, on a Fanuc controller, a G28 command tells the controller to home the machine. On a Fagor controller, that homing action is triggered when a G74 command is read.

posts.name: This isn't a game. Think about the repercussions.
posts.cooked:
Regardless of which Cut2D post you select, you can always modify one to meet whatever the needs of your controller. All Vectric products have this capability.  There is a short learning curve to understand both what your machine needs and what the commands in the Vectric post-processor file do, but spend a day and you’ll get it.

For school use, Vectric offers educational licenses, allowing the software to be installed on several machines.

You might consider V-Carve as an upgrade to Cut2D by the way. Lots of better features.

posts.cooked: If that Techno has an automatic tool changer DO NOT remove that G43 H… code. That code is critical to moving the tool to the correct height based on tool length.
